sols_latex:
From the hint we know that Matlab stores by row then by column.
Therefore the first line of code

\texttt{~A=zeros(3,2);}

would create a matrix of \textbf{zeros} with \textbf{3} rows and
\textbf{2} columns,

\begin{align*}
A=\begin{bmatrix}
0  &  0\\
0  &  0\\
0  &  0
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

The next lines of code

\texttt{~A(1,1)=5;}\\\texttt{~A(2,2)=3;}\\\texttt{~A(3,1)=1;}

would put a \textbf{5} in the \textbf{1}st row, \textbf{1}st column, a
\textbf{3} in the \textbf{2}nd row, \textbf{2}nd column and a \textbf{1}
in the \textbf{3}rd row, \textbf{1}st column and therefore,

\begin{align*}
A=\begin{bmatrix}
5  &  0\\
0  &  3\\
1  &  0
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

is our created matrix.

